07686nam a22009615i 9780228004615DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280046157 a10.1515/97802280046152doi  a(DE-B1597)657272  a(OCoLC)1159241122  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aR855.3b.W58 2020 7aMED0350002bisacsh04a61022300aWithout Compassion, There Is No Healthcare :bLeading with Care in a Technological Age /ced. by Brian D. Hodges, Jocelyn Bennett, Gail Paech. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource :b3 tables, 4 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tA Call to Caring -- tAcknowledgments -- tTechnology, Compassion, and the Future of Healthcare -- tComing to Terms with Compassion -- tCaring in a Digital Age: Exploring the Interface of Humans and Machines in the Provision of Compassionate Healthcare -- tPatient Engagement and Compassionate Care -- tCare in the Real World: Partial Perspectives on Compassion, Technology, and Equity -- tCultivating Compassion -- tHealthcare Workers as Recipients of Compassion: Resilience, Burnout, and Relationship -- tCompassion and Health Professional Education -- tCompassionate Leadership -- tToward Compassionate Healthcare Organizations -- tShaping the Future of Compassionate Care -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew technologies are transforming healthcare work and changing how patients interact with healthcare providers. As artificial intelligence systems, robotics, and data analytics become more sophisticated, some clinical tasks will become obsolete and others will be reconfigured. While it is not possible to predict these developments precisely, it is important to understand their inevitability and to prepare for the changes that lie ahead. Without Compassion, There Is No Healthcare argues that compassion must be upheld as the bedrock and guiding purpose of healthcare work. Emerging technologies have the potential to subvert this purpose but also to enable and expand it, creating new conduits for compassionate care. Cultivating these benefits and guarding against potential threats will require vigilance and determination from healthcare providers, educators, leaders, patients, and advocates. The contributors to this book show the way forward, bringing a diverse range of expertise to confront these challenges. Avoiding platitudes and simple dichotomies, they examine what compassion in healthcare means and how it can be practised, now and in the uncertain future. Without Compassion, There Is No Healthcare is a call to action. Drawing together a decade of evidence and insight generated by a community of leading scholars and practitioners committed to promoting compassionate care, it offers steady principles and practices to steer the way through times of technological change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBiomedical engineering. 0aCompassion. 0aEmpathy. 0aMedical care. 0aMedical personnel and patient. 0aMedical technology. 0aNurturing behavior. 7aMEDICAL / Health Care Delivery.2bisacsh1 aBennett, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennett, Jocelyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBriggs, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaukos, Deanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawford, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreede, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id